# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As feudal distinctions declined in the early modern era, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] With the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Others with property rights included husbandmen and free tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Many young people left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Under the Commonwealth, the country was relatively highly taxed, but gained access to English markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Restoration customs duties with England were re-established.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Economic conditions were generally favourable, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Union of 1707 there was a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Introductions included the English plough, foreign grasses, rye grass and clover, turnips and cabbages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Lands were enclosed, displacing the run rig system and free pasture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Marshes were drained, lime was put down, roads built, woods planted, drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 greatly improved the diet of the peasantry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw the eviction of hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers in central and southern Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In 1564 there were thirty-three days of continual frost, with rivers and lochs freezing over.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] This reduced the altitude at which crops could be grown and shortened the growing season by up to two months in extreme years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic, referred to as Scotland's "emergency granary".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] This was particularly from Poland through the port of Danzig, but later Königsberg and Riga, shipping Russian grain, and Swedish ports, would become important.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The trade was so significant that Scottish colonies were established in these ports.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] While the feudal tenures of barons were increasingly nominal local tenants-in-chief, who held legally held their land directly from the king and who by the sixteenth century were often the major local landholders in an area, grew in significance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As feudal distinctions declined, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds, roughly equivalent to the English gentlemen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below the lairds were a variety of groups, often ill-defined.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These included yeomen, later characterised by Walter Scott as "bonnet lairds", often owning substantial land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The practice of feuing (by which a tenant paid an entry sum and an annual feu duty, but could pass the land on to their heirs) meant that the number of people holding heritable possession of lands, which had previously been controlled by the church or nobility, expanded.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These and the lairds probably numbered about 10,000 by the seventeenth century and became what the government defined as heritors, on whom the financial and legal burdens of local government increasingly fell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below the substantial landholders were those engaged in subsistence agriculture, who made up the majority of the working population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Those with property rights included husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Below them were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the early modern era in Lowland rural society, as in England, many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Women acted as an important part of the workforce.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] As well as moving away from their families as farm servants, married women worked with their husbands around the farm, taking part in all the major agricultural tasks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They had a particular role as shearers in the harvest, forming most of the reaping team of the *bandwin*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The most common system was based on infield and outfield agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The more extensive outfield was used largely for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The area of arable land farmed by a family was notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in runrigs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] All farms combined livestock with arable farming, with cattle and sheep and goats in parts of the Highlands and all farms growing some grain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] However, there was some specialisation, with arable most important in the East and there was a tradition of sheep farming in the eastern Borders dating back to the arrival of new monastic orders in the twelfth century, which continued after the secularisation of the monasteries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In the early seventeenth century famine was relatively common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy, with the destruction of crops and the disruption of markets resulting in some of the most rapid price rises of the century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] After the Restoration the formal frontier with England was re-established, along with its customs duties.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Economic conditions were generally favourable from 1660 to 1688, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Arable farming grew in the Lowlands, particularly around the growing urban centres like Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Agricultural improvement began in the late seventeenth century in the Lothians and central Scotland, with the use of lime to combat the acidity of the soil, trees were planted, new crops introduced including sown grass and the rotation of crops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Three acts of parliament passed in 1695 allowed the consolidation of runrigs and the division of commonties and common pasture and small scale enclosures began to be carried out.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Highlanders had been droving cattle on the hoof to the Lowlands since at least the sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the 1680s the trade had expanded to the larger English markets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Cattle were crossed with larger Irish breeds and large parks were constructed by Galloway landholders to hold and fatten cattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] By the end of the century the drovers roads had become established, stretching down from the Highlands through south-west Scotland to north-east England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] From there some were driven to Norfolk to be fattened before being slaughtered in Smithfield for the London population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Specialisation continued, with the increasing commercialisation of sheep farming in the Borders as English markets opened up after the Union of Crowns in 1603 and dairy becoming a feature of farming in the western Lowlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw the generally favourable economic conditions that had dominated since the Restoration come to an end.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] There was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France from 1689 to 1691, caused by French protectionism and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The result was severe famine and depopulation, particularly in the north.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The famines of the 1690s were seen as particularly severe, partly because famine had become relatively rare in the second half of the seventeenth century, with only one year of dearth (in 1674) and the shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Climatic conditions began to improve in the early eighteenth century, although there were still bad years, like that of 1739–41.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Increasing contacts with England after the Union of 1707 led to a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The Society of Improvers was founded in 1723, including in its 300 members dukes, earls, lairds and landlords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Before the eighteenth century English books on husbandry had been available or reprinted in Scotland, but in the eighteenth century there were increasing numbers of titles published by Scottish authors in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] In the first half of the century these changes were limited to tenanted farms in East Lothian and the estates of a few enthusiasts, such as John Cockburn and Archibald Grant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Not all were successful, with Cockburn driving himself into bankruptcy, but the ethos of improvement spread among the landed classes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] The English plough, rye grass and clover, turnips and cabbages were introduced; lime was put down, marshes were drained, roads built and woods planted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Enclosures began to displace the runrig system and free pasture, creating the landscape of largely rectangular fields that characterises the Lowland Scottish landscape today.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] New farm buildings, often based on designs in patterns books, replaced the fermtoun and regional diversity was replaced with a standardisation of building forms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Smaller farms retained the linear outline of the longhouse, with dwelling house, barn and byre in a row, but in larger farms a three- or four-sided layout became common, separating the dwelling house from barns and servants quarters.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] There were also organisational changes that would have long term consequences, including the commutation of payments in kind for those in money, the granting of longer leases and the consolidation of smaller holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era] Tens of thousands of others emigrated to Canada or the United States, finding opportunities there to own and farm their own land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Vernacular architecture made use of local materials such as stone, turf and, where available, wood.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Most of the population was housed in small hamlets and isolated dwellings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The most common form of dwelling throughout Scotland was the long house, shared by humans and animals.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] About ten percent of the population lived in the burghs, in a mixture of half-timbered and stone houses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The impact of the Renaissance on Scottish architecture began in the reign of James III in the late fifteenth century with the rebuilding of royal palaces such as Linlithgow, and reached its peak under James V.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The Reformation had a major impact on ecclesiastical architecture from the mid-sixteenth century onward, resulting in simple church buildings, devoid of ornamentation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] From the 1560s great private houses were built in a distinctive style that became known as Scottish Baronial.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Such houses combined Renaissance features with those of Scottish castles and tower houses, resulting in larger, more comfortable residences.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After the Restoration in 1660, there was a fashion for grand private houses in designs influenced by the Palladian style and associated with the architects Sir William Bruce (1630–1710) and James Smith (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After the Act of Union in 1707, the threat of Jacobite Rebellions led to the building of military defences such as Fort George near Inverness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Scotland produced some of the most significant architects of the eighteenth century, including Colen Campbell, James Gibbs and William Adam, who all had a major influence on Georgian architecture across Britain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The influence of Gibbs led to churches that employed classical elements, with a pedimented rectangular plan and often with a steeple.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The vernacular architecture of Scotland, as elsewhere, made use of local materials and methods.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The homes of the poor were usually of very simple construction, and were built by groups of family and friends.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Stone is plentiful throughout Scotland and was a common building material, employed in both mortared and dry stone construction.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] As in English vernacular architecture, where wood was available, crucks (pairs of curved timbers) were often used to support the roof.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] With a lack of long span structural timber, the crucks were sometimes raised and supported on the walls.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Walls were often built of stone, and could have gaps filled with turf, or plastered with clay.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In some regions wattled walls filled in with turf were employed, sometimes on a stone base.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Turf-filled walls were not long-lasting, and had to be rebuilt perhaps as often as every two or three years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In some regions, including the south-west and around Dundee, solid clay walls were used, or combinations of clay, turf and straw, rendered with clay or lime to make them weatherproof.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Different regions used turfs, or thatch of broom, heather, straw or reeds for roofing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Most of the early modern population, in both the Lowlands and Highlands, was housed in small hamlets and isolated dwellings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] As the population expanded, some of these settlements were sub-divided to create new hamlets and more marginal land was settled, with *shielings* (clusters of huts occupied while summer pasture was being used for grazing), becoming permanent settlements.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The standard layout of a house throughout Scotland before agricultural improvement was a byre-dwelling or long house, with humans and livestock sharing a common roof, often separated by only a partition wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Contemporaries noted that cottages in the Highlands and Islands tended to be cruder, with single rooms, slit windows and earthen floors, often shared by a large family.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In contrast, many Lowland cottages had distinct rooms and chambers, were clad with plaster or paint and even had glazed windows.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Perhaps ten percent of the population lived in one of many burghs that had grown up in the later Medieval period, mainly in the east and south of the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] A characteristic of Scottish burghs was a long main street of tall buildings, with vennels, wynds and alleys leading off it, many of which survive today.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In towns, traditional thatched half-timbered houses were interspersed with the larger stone and slate-roofed town houses of merchants and the urban gentry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Many burghs acquired tollbooths in this period, which acted as town halls, courts and prisons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] They often had peels of bells or clock towers and the aspect of a fortress.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The Old Tolbooth, Edinburgh was rebuilt on the orders of Mary Queen of Scots from 1561 and housed the parliament until the end of the 1630s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Other examples can be seen at Tain, Culross and Stonehaven, often showing influences from the Low Countries in their crow-stepped gables and steeples.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The extensive building and rebuilding of royal palaces probably began under James III (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1460–88), accelerated under James IV (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1488–1513) and reached its peak under James V (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The influence of Renaissance architecture is reflected in these buildings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Linlithgow was first constructed under James I (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1406–27), under the direction of master of work John de Waltoun and was referred to as a palace from 1429, apparently the first use of this term in the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] It was extended under James III and resembled a quadrangular, corner-towered Italian signorial palace or *palatium ad moden castri* (a castle-style palace), combining classical symmetry with neo-chivalric imagery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] There is evidence that Italian masons were employed by James IV, in whose reign Linlithgow was completed and other palaces were rebuilt with Italianate proportions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In 1536 James V visited France for his marriage to Madeleine of Valois and would have come in contact with French Renaissance architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] His second marriage to Mary of Guise two years later may have resulted in longer-term connections and influences.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Architecture from his reign largely disregarded the insular style of England under Henry VIII and adopted forms that were recognisably European.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Rather than slavishly copying continental forms, most Scottish architecture incorporated elements of these styles into traditional local patterns, adapting them to Scottish idioms and materials (particularly stone and harl).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Some decorative wood carvings were made by French craftsmen, who like Andrew Mansioun, settled in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The building at Linlithgow was followed by rebuilding at Holyrood Palace, Falkland Palace, Stirling Castle and Edinburgh Castle, described by Roger Mason as "some of the finest examples of Renaissance architecture in Britain".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Many of the building programs were planned and financed by James Hamilton of Finnart, Steward of the Royal Household and Master of Works to James V.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He was also responsible for the architectural works at Blackness Castle, Rothesay Castle, the house at Crawfordjohn, the New Inn in the St Andrews Cathedral Priory and the lodging at Balmerino Abbey for the ailing Queen Madeleine.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] For the six years of her regency Mary of Guise employed an Italian military architect, Lorenzo Pomarelli.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Work undertaken for James VI demonstrated continued Renaissance influences; the Chapel Royal at Stirling has a classical entrance built in 1594 and the North Wing of Linlithgow, built in 1618, uses classical pediments.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Similar themes can be seen in the private houses of aristocrats, as in Mar's Wark, Stirling (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1570) and Crichton Castle, built for the Earl of Bothwell in 1580s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] From about 1560, the Reformation revolutionised church architecture in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Calvinists rejected ornamentation in places of worship, seeing no need for elaborate buildings divided up for the purpose of ritual.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] This resulted in the widespread destruction of Medieval church furnishings, ornaments and decoration.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] New churches were built and existent churches adapted for reformed services, particularly by placing the pulpit centrally in the church, as preaching was at the centre of worship.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Many of the earliest buildings were simple gabled rectangles, a style that continued into the seventeenth century, as at Dunnottar Castle in the 1580s, Greenock (1591) and Durness (1619).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] These churches often have windows on the south wall (and none on the north), which became a characteristic of Reformation kirks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] There were continuities with pre-Reformation materials, with some churches using rubble for walls, as at Kemback in Fife (1582).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Others employed dressed stone and a few added wooden steeples, as at Burntisland (1592).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The church of Greyfriars, Edinburgh, built between 1602 and 1620, used a rectangular layout with a largely Gothic form, but that at Dirleton (1612), had a more sophisticated classical style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] A variation of the rectangular church developed in post-Reformation Scotland, and often used when adapting existing churches, was the T-shaped plan, which allowed the maximum number of parishioners to be near the pulpit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Examples can be seen at Kemback and Prestonpans after 1595.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] This plan continued to be used into the seventeenth century as at Weem (1600), Anstruther Easter, Fife (1634–44) and New Cumnock (1657).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In the seventeenth century a Greek cross plan was used for churches such as Cawdor (1619) and Fenwick (1643).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In most of these cases one arm of the cross would have been closed off as a laird's aisle, meaning that they were in effect T-plan churches.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The unique style of great private houses in Scotland, later known as Scots Baronial, originated in the 1560s and may have been influenced by the French masons brought to Scotland to work on royal palaces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] It kept many of the features of the high walled Medieval castles that had been largely made obsolete by gunpowder weapons and also drew on the tower houses and peel towers that had been built in their hundreds by local lords since the fourteenth century, particularly in the borders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] These houses abandoned the defensible curtain walls of castles, being fortified refuges that were designed to outlast a raid, rather than a sustained siege.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] They were usually of three stories, typically crowned with a parapet, projecting on corbels, continuing into circular bartizans at each corner.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The new houses built from the late sixteenth century by nobles and lairds were primarily designed for comfort, not for defence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] They retained many of the external features that had become associated with nobility but with a larger ground plan, classically a "Z-plan" of a rectangular block with towers, as at Colliston Castle (1583) and Claypotts Castle (1569–88).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Towers were typically set in gated yards enclosing lower buildings, such as kitchens, breweries, and stables.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The yard buildings at the House of Fiddes were listed in a schedule of roofing works in 1624.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] There was a "womanhouse", where domestic textile work such as spinning was carried out.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] William Wallace, the king's master mason from 1617 until his death in 1631, was particularly influential.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He worked on the rebuilding of the collapsed North Range of Linlithgow from 1618, Winton House for George Seton, 3rd Earl of Winton, Moray House for the Countess of Home, and began work on Heriot's Hospital, Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He adopted a distinctive style that applied elements of Scottish fortification and Flemish influences to a Renaissance plan similar to that used at Château d'Ancy-le-Franc.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] This style can be seen in lords' houses built at Caerlaverlock (1620), Moray House, Edinburgh (1628) and Drumlanrig Castle (1675–89), and was highly influential until the Baronial style gave way to the grander English forms associated with Inigo Jones in the later seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] During the turbulent era of the Civil Wars and the incorporation of Scotland into a Commonwealth of England, Scotland and Ireland, significant building in Scotland was largely confined to military architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Polygonal fortresses with triangular bastions in the style of the trace italienne were built to house English soldiers at Ayr, Perth and Leith, and 20 smaller forts were built as far apart as Orkney and Stornoway.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Control of the Highlands was secured by new strongpoints at Inverlocky and Inverness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The universities saw an improvement in their funding, as they were given income from deaneries, defunct bishoprics and the excise, allowing the completion of buildings including the college in the High Street in Glasgow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After the Restoration in 1660, large-scale building began again, influenced by a growing interest in Classicism.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1630–1710) is considered "the effective founder of classical architecture in Scotland" and was the key figure in introducing the Palladian style to the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Andrea Palladio (1508–80) was an influential architect who worked in the region of Venice in the sixteenth century and whose buildings are characterised by symmetry, fine proportion and formal elements drawn from Ancient Classical architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In England the introduction of the Palladian style is associated with Inigo Jones (1573–1652).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Bruce's architectural style incorporated Palladian elements and was influenced by Jones, but also borrowed from the Italian Baroque and was most strongly influenced by Sir Christopher Wren's (1632–1723) interpretation of the Baroque in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Bruce popularised a style of country house among the Scottish nobility that encouraged a move towards a more leisure-oriented architecture already adopted in continental Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He built and remodelled country houses, including Thirlestane Castle and Prestonfield House.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Among his most significant work was his own Palladian mansion at Kinross, built on the Loch Leven estate he had purchased in 1675.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Bruce's houses were predominantly built using well-cut ashlar masonry on the façades; rubble stonework was used only for internal walls.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] As the Surveyor and Overseer of the Royal Works Bruce undertook the rebuilding of the Royal Palace of Holyroodhouse in the 1670s, giving the palace its present appearance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After the death of Charles II in 1685, Bruce lost political favour, and following the Glorious Revolution of 1688 he was imprisoned more than once as a suspected Jacobite.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] 1645–1731) worked as a mason on Bruce's rebuilding of Holyrood Palace.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In 1683 he was appointed Surveyor and Overseer of the Royal Works, responsible for the palace's maintenance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] With his father-in-law, the master mason Robert Mylne (1633–1710), Smith worked on Caroline Park in Edinburgh (1685), and Drumlanrig Castle (1680s).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Smith's country houses followed the pattern established by William Bruce, with hipped roofs and pedimented fronts, in a plain but handsome Palladian style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Hamilton Palace (1695) was fronted by giant Corinthian columns, and a pedimented entrance, but was otherwise restrained.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Dalkeith Palace (1702–10) was modelled after William of Orange's palace at Het Loo in the Netherlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] By the later seventeenth century both the Presbyterian and Episcopalian wings of the church had adopted the modestly sized and plain form of churches that had emerged after the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Most had a centralised plan with two or three arms, in a rectangular or T-planned arrangement.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Steeples continued to be a major feature, either centrally on the long axis, or on an end gable, as had been the case in pre-Reformation churches.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] As a result, there was little of the Baroque extravagance in church building seen on the continent and England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Some minor innovations may indicate a move back toward episcopacy in the Restoration era.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Lauder Church was built by Bruce in 1673 for the Duke of Lauderdale, who championed the bishops in the reign of Charles II.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The Gothic windows may have emphasised antiquity, but its basic Greek cross plan remained within the existing common framework of new churches.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The major exceptions to the common Greek cross plan are in the work of Smith, who had become a Jesuit in his youth.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] These included the rebuilding of Holyrood Abbey undertaken for James VII in 1687, which was outfitted in an elaborate style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In 1691 Smith designed the mausoleum of Sir George Mackenzie of Rosehaugh, in Greyfriars Kirkyard, a circular structure modelled on the Tempietto di San Pietro, designed by Donato Bramante (1444–1514).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The drive to Episcopalian forms of worship may have resulted in more linear patterns, including rectangular plans with the pulpit at the end opposite the entrance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The Latin Cross form increasingly popular in Counter Reformation Catholicism, was also used, as in Smith's Canongate Kirk (1688–90), but the Presbyterian revolution of 1689–90 occurred before its completion and the chancel was blocked up, effectively transforming it into a T-plan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After the Act of Union of 1707, growing prosperity in Scotland led to a spate of new building, both public and private.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] The threat of Jacobite insurrection or invasion meant that Scotland saw more military building than England in this period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Military structures relied on the strength of inclined and angled engineered masonry and earthen toppings to deflect and absorb artillery fire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] This spate of military building culminated in the construction of Fort George near Inverness (1748–69), with its projecting bastions and redoubts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Scotland produced some of the most significant architects of the early eighteenth century, including Colen Campbell (1676–1729), James Gibbs (1682–1754) and William Adam (1689–1748), all of whom were influenced by Classical architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Campbell was influenced by the Palladian style and has been credited with founding Georgian architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Architectural historian Howard Colvin has speculated that he was associated with James Smith and may even have been his pupil.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He spent most of his career in Italy and England and developed a rivalry with fellow Scot James Gibbs, who trained in Rome and also practised mainly in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Campbell's architectural style incorporated Palladian elements, as well as forms from the Italian Baroque and Inigo Jones, but was most strongly influenced by Sir Christopher Wren's interpretation of the Baroque.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] William Adam, the foremost Scottish architect of his time, designed and built numerous country houses and public buildings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Among his best known works are Hopetoun House near Edinburgh, and Duff House in Banff.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] His individual, exuberant, style was built on the Palladian style, but with Baroque motifs inspired by the work of John Vanbrugh and Continental architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] After his death, his sons Robert and John took on the family business and became the leading British architects of the second half of the century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] In the 18th century established patterns of church building continued, with T-shaped plans with steeples on the long side, as at New Church, Dumfries (1724–27), and Newbattle Parish Church (1727–29).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] William Adam's Hamilton Parish Church (1729–32), was a Greek cross plan inscribed in a circle, while John Douglas's Killin Church (1744) was octagonal.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Scots-born architect James Gibbs was highly influential on British ecclesiastical architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] He introduced a consciously antique style in his rebuilding of St Martin-in-the-Fields, London, with a massive, steepled portico and rectangular, side-aisled plan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Similar patterns in Scotland can be seen at St Andrew's in the Square (1737–59), designed by Allan Dreghorn and built by the master mason Mungo Nasmyth, and at the smaller Donibristle Chapel (completed in 1731), designed by Alexander McGill.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/architecture-in-early-modern-scotland] Nicholas West, Aberdeen (1752–55), had the same rectangular plan, with a nave-and-aisles, barrel-vaulted layout with superimposed pedimented front.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Devotional art before the Reformation included books and images commissioned in the Netherlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Before the Reformation in the mid-sixteenth century the interiors of Scottish churches were often elaborate and colourful, with sacrament houses and monumental effigies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Scotland's ecclesiastical art paid a heavy toll as a result of Reformation iconoclasm, with the almost total loss of medieval stained glass, religious sculpture and paintings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In about 1500 the Scottish monarchy turned to the recording of royal likenesses in panel portraits.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] More impressive are the works or artists imported from the continent, particularly the Netherlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The tradition of royal portrait painting in Scotland was probably disrupted by the minorities and regencies it underwent for much of the sixteenth century, but it flourished after the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] James VI employed Flemish artists Arnold Bronckorst and Adrian Vanson, who have left behind a visual record of the king and major figures at the court.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The first significant native artist was George Jamesone, who was succeeded by a series of portrait painters as the fashion moved down the social scale to lairds and burgesses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The loss of ecclesiastical patronage that resulted from the Reformation created a crisis for native craftsmen and artists, who turned to secular patrons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] One result of this was the flourishing of Scottish Renaissance painted ceilings and walls.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Other forms of domestic decoration included tapestries and stone and wood carving.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In the first half of the eighteenth century there was an increasing professionalisation and organisation of art.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Large numbers of artists took the grand tour to Italy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Luke was founded as a society for artists in 1729.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] It included among its members Allan Ramsay, who emerged as one of the most important British artists of the era.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] There are also a relatively large number of elaborate devotional books from the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries, usually produced in the Netherlands and France for Scottish patrons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] These include the prayer book commissioned by Robert Blackadder, Bishop of Glasgow, between 1484 and 1492 and the Flemish illustrated book of hours, known as the Hours of James IV of Scotland, given by James IV to Margaret Tudor after 1503 and described by D.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Caldwell as "perhaps the finest medieval manuscript to have been commissioned for Scottish use".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Before the Reformation in the mid-sixteenth century the interiors of Scottish churches were often elaborate and colourful.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Particularly in the north-east of the country there were highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Kinkell from 1524 and Deskford from 1541.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Monumental effigies in churches were usually fully coloured and gilded and dedicated to members of the clergy, knights and their wives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In contrast to England, where the fashion for stone-carved monuments gave way to monumental brasses, in Scotland they continued to be produced until the end of the Medieval period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] These include the very elaborate Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas and the tomb built for Alexander McLeod (d.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The only significant surviving pre-Reformation stained glass in Scotland is a window of four roundels in the St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Magdalen Chapel of Cowgate, Edinburgh, completed in 1544.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Wood carving can be seen at King's College, Aberdeen and Dunblane Cathedral.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In the West Highlands, where there had been a hereditary caste of monumental sculptors, the uncertainty and loss of patronage caused by the rejection of monuments in the Reformation meant that they moved into another branches of the Gaelic learned orders or took up other occupations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The lack of transfer of carving skills is noticeable in the decline in quality when gravestones were next commissioned from the start of the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Prior, the nature of the Scottish Reformation may have had wider effects, limiting the creation of a culture of public display and meaning that art was channelled into more austere forms of expression with an emphasis on private and domestic restraint.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Around 1500, about the same time as in England, Scottish monarchs turned to the recording of royal likenesses in panel portraits, painted in oils on wood, perhaps as a form of political expression.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In 1502 James IV paid for delivery of portraits of the Tudor household, probably by the "Inglishe payntour" named "Mynours," who stayed in Scotland to paint the king and his new bride Margaret Tudor the following year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] "Mynours" was Maynard Wewyck, a Flemish painter who usually worked for Henry VII in London.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] As in England, the monarchy may have had model portraits of royalty used for copies and reproductions, but the versions of native royal portraits that survive are generally crude by continental standards.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Much more impressive are the works or artists imported from the continent, particularly the Netherlands, generally considered the centre of painting in the Northern Renaissance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The products of these connections included a fine portrait of William Elphinstone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] It is one of the earliest representations of a Scottish subject to survive and was probably painted by a Scots artist using Flemish techniques.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The tradition of royal portrait painting in Scotland was disrupted by the minorities and regencies it underwent for much of the sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In his majority James V was probably more concerned with architectural expressions of royal identity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Mary Queen of Scots had been brought up in the French court, where she was drawn and painted by major European artists, but she did not commission any adult portraits, with the exception of the joint portrait with her second husband Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] This may have reflected an historic Scottish pattern, where heraldic display or an elaborate tomb were considered more important than a portrait.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Portraiture began to flourish after the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] There were anonymously painted portraits of important individuals, including miniatures of James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell and his wife Jean Gordon (1556).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Artists from the Low Countries remained important.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Hans Eworth, who had been court painter to Mary I of England, painted a number of Scottish subjects in the 1560s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He painted James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray in 1561 and two years later he painted a joint portrait of the young Darnley and his brother Charles Stuart.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Lord Seton, Master of the Royal Household commissioned two portraits in the Netherlands in the 1570s, one of himself and one a family portrait.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] A specific type of Scottish picture is the "vendetta portrait", designed to keep alive the memory of an atrocity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] There was an attempt to produce a series of portraits of Scottish kings in panel portraits, probably for the royal entry of the fifteen-year-old James VI in 1579, which are Medieval in form.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In James VI's personal reign, Renaissance forms of portraiture began to dominate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He employed two Flemish artists, Arnold Bronckorst in the early 1580s and Adrian Vanson from around 1584 to 1602, who have left us a visual record of the king and major figures at the court.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] However, the Union of Crowns in 1603 removed a major source of artistic patronage in Scotland as James VI and his court moved to London.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The result has been seen as a shift "from crown to castle", as the nobility and local lairds became the major sources of patronage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] By the seventeenth century the fashion for portraiture had spread down the social order to lairds such as Colin Campbell of Glenorchy and John Napier of Merchiston.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The first significant native artist was George Jamesone of Aberdeen (1589/90-1644), who, having trained in the Netherlands, became one of the most successful portrait painters of the reign of Charles I.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He trained the Baroque artist John Michael Wright (1617–94), who painted both Scottish and English subjects.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The Flemish-Spanish painter John Baptist Medina (1659–1710) came to Scotland in 1693 and became the leading Scottish portrait painter of his generation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Among his best known works are a group of about 30 oval bust-lengths, including a self-portrait, in Surgeons' Hall, Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He trained his son, also John, and William Aikman (1682–1731), who became the leading portrait painter of the next generation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Aikman migrated to London in 1723, and from this point until the late eighteenth century, most Scottish painters of note followed him.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The loss of ecclesiastical patronage that resulted from the Reformation, created a crisis for native craftsmen and artists, who turned to secular patrons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] One result of this was the flourishing of Scottish Renaissance painted ceilings and walls, with large numbers of private houses of burgesses, lairds and lords gaining often highly detailed and coloured patterns and scenes, of which over a hundred examples are known to have existed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] These were undertaken by unnamed Scottish artists using continental pattern books that often led to the incorporation of humanist moral and philosophical symbolism, with elements that call on heraldry, piety, classical myths and allegory.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The earliest surviving example is at the Hamilton palace of Kinneil, West Lothian, decorated in the 1550s for the then regent the James Hamilton, Earl of Arran.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Other examples include the ceiling at Prestongrange House, undertaken in 1581 for Mark Kerr, Commendator of Newbattle, and the long gallery at Pinkie House, painted for Alexander Seton, Earl of Dunfermline in 1621.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Some furniture was painted, and James VI commissioned a decorative painter, James Workman to make a board for playing the Game of the Goose.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Records indicate that Scottish palaces were adorned by rich tapestries, like those that depicted scenes from the *Iliad* and *Odyssey* set up for James IV at Holyrood.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Some of this was undertaken by exclusive professional embroiders, but needlework was part of female education at all levels of society.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Some of these tapestries were produced by noble ladies, such as the bed valances made by Katherine Ruthven for her marriage in 1551 to Campbell of Glenorchy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] These are the oldest surviving examples of Scottish produced embroidery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] They display the couple's initials, arms and the story of Adam and Eve.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] A carpet designed to cover a table may be connected to the marriage of Katherine Oliphant, which has her initials, arms, biblical verses and (perhaps as a pun on her name) an elephant.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Much of the needle work of the sixteenth century has been attributed, probably erroneously, to Mary, Queen of Scots.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] It is thought that she did contribute to the Oxburgh Hangings while imprisoned in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Although tradition of stone and wood carving in churches largely ended at the Reformation, it continued in royal palaces, the great houses of the nobility and even the humbler homes of lairds and burgesses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The intricate lid of the fourteenth-century Bute mazer, carved from a single piece of whale bone, was probably created in the early sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] At Stirling Castle, stone carvings on the royal palace from the reign of James V are taken from German patterns, and, like the surviving carved oak portrait roundels from the King's Presence Chamber, known as the Stirling Heads, they include contemporary, biblical and classical figures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] These, and the elaborate Renaissance fountain at Linlithgow Palace (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] 1538.), suggest that there was a workshop with an established connected with the court in the early sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] James V and his successors employed a versatile French craftsman and wood carver, Andrew Mansioun, who settled in Edinburgh and trained apprentices.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Some of the finest domestic wood carving is in the Beaton panels made for Arbroath Abbey and at Huntly Castle, rebuilt for George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly in the early seventeenth century, which focused on heraldic images.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Their "popish" overtones led to them being damaged by an occupying Covenanter army in 1640.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] From the seventeenth century, as domestic architecture for the nobility was increasingly for comfort, rather than fortification, there was elaborate use of carving in carved pediments, fireplaces, heraldic arms and classical motifs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Plasterwork also began to be used, often depicting flowers and cherubs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Richly carved decoration on ordinary houses was common in the period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] There is also the heraldic carving, such as the royal arms at Holyrood Palace, designed by the Dutch painter Jacob de Wet in 1677.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The tradition of carving also survived in work like the carved stone panels in the garden of Edzell Castle (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] 1600), the now lost carving done for Edinburgh and Glasgow universities in the seventeenth-century and in the many elaborate sundials of the seventeenth century, like those at Newbattle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The growing importance of royal art can be seen in the post of Painter and Limner, created in 1702 for George Ogilvie.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The duties included drawing pictures of the Monarch's person, his successors and members of the royal family, for the decoration of royal houses and palaces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] However, from 1723 to 1823 the office was a sinecure held by members of the Abercrombie family, not necessarily connected with artistic ability.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] They tutored artists and have been credited with the inception of the tradition of Scottish landscape painting that would come to fruition from the late eighteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Italy became an important point of reference for Scottish artists, with many taking the Grand Tour there to paint, sample the art and learn from Italian masters.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] In 1729 there was an attempt to found a school of painting in Edinburgh as the Academy of St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Luke, named after the Renaissance Accademia di San Luca in Rome.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Its president was George Marshall, a painter of still lives and portraits, and its treasurer was the engraver Richard Cooper.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Other members included Cooper's student Robert Strange, the two younger Nories, the portrait painters John Alexander (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] The success of the group was limited by its associations with Jacobitism, with Strange printing bank notes for the rebels.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Alexander was a great grandson of George Jamesone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He studied in London and Rome, returning to Edinburgh about 1720 where he painted the Baroque *The Rape of Proserpine*, for the roof of a staircase at Gordon Castle and numerous portraits.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] Ramsay emerged as the most distinguished alumni of the academy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He studied in Sweden, London and Italy before basing himself in Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] There he established himself as a leading portrait painter to the Scottish nobility, before moving to London in 1757.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/art-in-early-modern-scotland] He made occasional return visits to Edinburgh to undertake commissions for the nobility and gentry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The **Baltic Sea** is an arm of the Atlantic Ocean that is enclosed by the countries of Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, Sweden, and the North and Central European Plain regions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is the world's largest brackish water basin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The sea stretches from 53°N to 66°N latitude and from 10°E to 30°E longitude.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is a shelf sea and marginal sea of the Atlantic with limited water exchange between the two, making it an inland sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea drains through the Danish Straits into the Kattegat by way of the Øresund, Great Belt and Little Belt.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It includes the Gulf of Bothnia (divided into the Bothnian Bay and the Bothnian Sea), the Gulf of Finland, the Gulf of Riga and the Bay of Gdańsk.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The "Baltic Proper" is bordered on its northern edge, at latitude 60°N, by Åland and the Gulf of Bothnia, on its northeastern edge by the Gulf of Finland, on its eastern edge by the Gulf of Riga, and in the west by the Swedish part of the southern Scandinavian Peninsula.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is connected by artificial waterways to the White Sea via the White Sea–Baltic Canal and to the German Bight of the North Sea via the Kiel Canal.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The narrowest part of Little Belt is the "Middelfart Sund" near Middelfart.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Geographers widely agree that the preferred physical border between the Baltic and North Seas is the Langelandsbælt (the southern part of the Great Belt strait near Langeland) and the Drogden-Sill strait.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Drogden Sill is situated north of Køge Bugt and connects Dragør in the south of Copenhagen to Malmö; it is used by the Øresund Bridge, including the *Drogden Tunnel*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] By this definition, the Danish Straits is part of the entrance, but the Bay of Mecklenburg and the Bay of Kiel are parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Another usual border is the line between Falsterbo, Sweden, and Stevns Klint, Denmark, as this is the southern border of Øresund.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is also the border between the shallow southern Øresund (with a typical depth of 5–10 meters only) and notably deeper water.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Drogden Sill (depth of 7 m (23 ft)) sets a limit to Øresund and Darss Sill (depth of 18 m (59 ft)), and a limit to the Belt Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The shallow sills are obstacles to the flow of heavy salt water from the Kattegat into the basins around Bornholm and Gotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Kattegat and the southwestern Baltic Sea are well oxygenated and have a rich biology.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The remainder of the Sea is brackish, poor in oxygen, and in species.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Thus, statistically, the more of the entrance that is included in its definition, the healthier the Baltic appears; conversely, the more narrowly it is defined, the more endangered its biology appears.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The precise origin of the name is unknown.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Tacitus called it the Suebic Sea, Latin: *Mare Suebicum* after the Germanic people of the Suebi, and Ptolemy *Sarmatian Ocean* after the Sarmatians, but the first to name it the *Baltic Sea* (Medieval Latin: *Mare Balticum*) was the eleventh-century German chronicler Adam of Bremen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It might be connected to the Germanic word *belt*, a name used for two of the Danish Straits, the Belts, while others claim it to be directly derived from the source of the Germanic word, Latin *balteus* "belt".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Adam of Bremen himself compared the sea with a belt, stating that it is so named because it stretches through the land as a belt (*Balticus, eo quod in modum baltei longo tractu per Scithicas regiones tendatur usque in Greciam*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] He might also have been influenced by the name of a legendary island mentioned in the *Natural History* of Pliny the Elder.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Pliny mentions an island named *Baltia* (or *Balcia*) with reference to accounts of Pytheas and Xenophon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is possible that Pliny refers to an island named Basilia ("the royal") in *On the Ocean* by Pytheas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] *Baltia* also might be derived from "belt", and therein mean "near belt of sea, strait".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Others have suggested that the name of the island originates from the Proto-Indo-European root **bʰel* meaning "white, fair", which may echo the naming of seas after colours relating to the cardinal points (as per Black Sea and Red Sea).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This **bʰel* root and basic meaning were retained in Lithuanian (as *baltas*), Latvian (as *balts*) and Slavic (as *bely*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] On this basis, a related hypothesis holds that the name originated from this Indo-European root via a Baltic language such as Lithuanian.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Yet another explanation is that the name originally meant "enclosed sea, bay" as opposed to open sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the Middle Ages the sea was known by a variety of names.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The name Baltic Sea became dominant after 1600.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Usage of *Baltic* and similar terms to denote the region east of the sea started only in the 19th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea was known in ancient Latin language sources as *Mare Suebicum* or even *Mare Germanicum*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] At the time of the Roman Empire, the Baltic Sea was known as the *Mare Suebicum* or *Mare Sarmaticum*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Tacitus in his AD 98 *Agricola* and *Germania* described the Mare Suebicum, named for the Suebi tribe, during the spring months, as a brackish sea where the ice broke apart and chunks floated about.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Suebi eventually migrated southwest to temporarily reside in the Rhineland area of modern Germany, where their name survives in the historic region known as Swabia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Jordanes called it the *Germanic Sea* in his work, the *Getica*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the early Middle Ages, Norse (Scandinavian) merchants built a trade empire all around the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Later, the Norse fought for control of the Baltic against Wendish tribes dwelling on the southern shore.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Norse also used the rivers of Russia for trade routes, finding their way eventually to the Black Sea and southern Russia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This Norse-dominated period is referred to as the Viking Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Since the Viking Age, the Scandinavians have referred to the Baltic Sea as *Austmarr* ("Eastern Sea").
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] "Eastern Sea", appears in the *Heimskringla* and *Eystra salt* appears in *Sörla þáttr*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Saxo Grammaticus recorded in *Gesta Danorum* an older name, *Gandvik*, *-vik* being Old Norse for "bay", which implies that the Vikings correctly regarded it as an inlet of the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Another form of the name, "Grandvik", attested in at least one English translation of *Gesta Danorum*, is likely to be a misspelling.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In addition to fish the sea also provides amber, especially from its southern shores within today's borders of Poland, Russia and Lithuania.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] First mentions of amber deposits on the South Coast of the Baltic Sea date back to the 12th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The bordering countries have also traditionally exported lumber, wood tar, flax, hemp and furs by ship across the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Sweden had from early medieval times exported iron and silver mined there, while Poland had and still has extensive salt mines.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Thus, the Baltic Sea has long been crossed by much merchant shipping.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The lands on the Baltic's eastern shore were among the last in Europe to be converted to Christianity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This finally happened during the Northern Crusades: Finland in the twelfth century by Swedes, and what are now Estonia and Latvia in the early thirteenth century by Danes and Germans (Livonian Brothers of the Sword).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Teutonic Order gained control over parts of the southern and eastern shore of the Baltic Sea, where they set up their monastic state.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Lithuania was the last European state to convert to Christianity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the period between the 8th and 14th centuries, there was much piracy in the Baltic from the coasts of Pomerania and Prussia, and the Victual Brothers held Gotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Starting in the 11th century, the southern and eastern shores of the Baltic were settled by migrants mainly from Germany, a movement called the *Ostsiedlung* ("east settling").
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Other settlers were from the Netherlands, Denmark, and Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Polabian Slavs were gradually assimilated by the Germans.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Denmark gradually gained control over a large portion of the Baltic coast, until it lost many of its possessions after being defeated in the 1227 Battle of Bornhöved.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Between the 13th and 17th centuries the Baltic Sea was, depending on the period, dominated by the Netherlands, Germany, Sweden and Russia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the 13th to 16th centuries, the strongest economic force in Northern Europe was the Hanseatic League, a federation of merchant cities around the Baltic Sea and the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, Poland, Denmark, and Sweden fought wars for *Dominium maris baltici* ("Lordship over the Baltic Sea").
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Eventually, it was Sweden that virtually encompassed the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In Sweden, the sea was then referred to as *Mare Nostrum Balticum* ("Our Baltic Sea").
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The goal of Swedish warfare during the 17th century was to make the Baltic Sea an all-Swedish sea (*Ett Svenskt innanhav*), something that was accomplished except the part between Riga in Latvia and Stettin in Pomerania.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] However, the Dutch dominated the Baltic trade in the seventeenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the eighteenth century, Russia and Prussia became the leading powers over the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Sweden's defeat in the Great Northern War brought Russia to the eastern coast.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Russia became and remained a dominating power in the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Russia's Peter the Great saw the strategic importance of the Baltic and decided to found his new capital, Saint Petersburg, at the mouth of the Neva river at the east end of the Gulf of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] There was much trading not just within the Baltic region but also with the North Sea region, especially eastern England and the Netherlands: their fleets needed the Baltic timber, tar, flax, and hemp.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] During the Crimean War, a joint British and French fleet attacked the Russian fortresses in the Baltic; the case is also known as the Åland War.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] They bombarded Sveaborg, which guards Helsinki; and Kronstadt, which guards Saint Petersburg; and they destroyed Bomarsund in Åland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] After the unification of Germany in 1871, the whole southern coast became German.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] World War I was partly fought in the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] After 1920 Poland was granted access to the Baltic Sea at the expense of Germany by the Polish Corridor and enlarged the port of Gdynia in rivalry with the port of the Free City of Danzig.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] After the Nazis' rise to power, Germany reclaimed the Memelland and after the outbreak of the Eastern Front (World War II) occupied the Baltic states.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In 1945, the Baltic Sea became a mass grave for retreating soldiers and refugees on torpedoed troop transports.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The sinking of the *Wilhelm Gustloff* remains the worst maritime disaster in history, killing (very roughly) 9,000 people.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In 2005, a Russian group of scientists found over five thousand airplane wrecks, sunken warships, and other material, mainly from World War II, on the bottom of the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Since the end of World War II, various nations, including the Soviet Union, the United Kingdom and the United States have disposed of chemical weapons in the Baltic Sea, raising concerns of environmental contamination.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Today, fishermen occasionally find some of these materials: the most recent available report from the Helsinki Commission notes that four small scale catches of chemical munitions representing approximately 105 kg (231 lb) of material were reported in 2005.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This is a reduction from the 25 incidents representing 1,110 kg (2,450 lb) of material in 2003.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Government refuses to disclose the exact coordinates of the wreck sites.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Deteriorating bottles leak mustard gas and other substances, thus slowly poisoning a substantial part of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In addition to chemicals, tons of German ammunition were dumped into the Baltic after the war at the behest of the Allies, who wanted to ensure that they would not start another war.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] By 2025, these were leaking contaminants into the water and the German government was piloting solutions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] After 1945, the German population was expelled from all areas east of the Oder-Neisse line, making room for new Polish and Russian settlement.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Poland gained most of the southern shore.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Soviet Union gained another access to the Baltic with the Kaliningrad Oblast, that had been part of German-settled East Prussia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic states on the eastern shore were annexed by the Soviet Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic then separated opposing military blocs: NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] During the Cold War the Baltic Sea remained on the periphery of the main axis of confrontation between these two blocs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Neutral Sweden developed incident weapons to defend its territorial waters after the Swedish submarine incidents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This border status restricted trade and travel.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It ended only after the collapse of the Communist regimes in Central and Eastern Europe in the late 1980s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Finland and Sweden joined NATO in 2023 and 2024, respectively, making the Baltic Sea almost entirely surrounded by the alliance's members, leading some commentators to label the sea a "NATO lake".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] However, the legal status of the sea has not changed and it is still open to all nations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Such an arrangement has also existed for the European Union (EU) since May 2004 following the accession of the Baltic states and Poland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The remaining non-NATO and non-EU shore areas are Russian: the Saint Petersburg area and the Kaliningrad Oblast exclave.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea today is of significant economic and security importance due to its dense network of submarine cables, energy pipelines, ports and offshore energy platforms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In recent years, there have been a number of incidents of sabotage in the Baltic Sea, resulting in damage to critical infrastructures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The most notable incidents include the Nord Stream pipelines sabotage in 2022, where a series of underwater explosions destroyed both Nord Stream 1 and 2.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In 2023, there was another incident involving the Balticconnector gas pipeline and a nearby data cable, which were damaged by the Hong Kong-flagged container ship NewNew Polar Bear.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Other significant incidents include the recent damage to several undersea communication cables.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The most recent incident of relevance was the rupture of the Estlink 2 cable in late 2024.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is suspected that the oil tanker Eagle S, believed to be part of a Russian shadow fleet, is responsible.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] These events followed a series of responses from both NATO and the EU.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In response, NATO Baltic Sea states have increased their naval presence in the Baltic Sea, and the NATO operation Baltic Sentry was established.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Simultaneously, the EU has implemented a series of measures designed to enhance the protection of critical maritime infrastructure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The EU has also underscored the commitment to strengthening cooperation with NATO.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Winter storms begin arriving in the region during October.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] These have caused numerous shipwrecks, and contributed to the extreme difficulties of rescuing passengers of the ferry MS *Estonia* en route from Tallinn, Estonia, to Stockholm, Sweden, in September 1994, which claimed the lives of 852 people.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Older, wood-based shipwrecks such as the *Vasa* tend to remain well-preserved, as the Baltic's cold and brackish water does not suit the shipworm.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Storm surge floods are generally taken to occur when the water level is more than one metre above normal.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In Warnemünde about 110 floods occurred from 1950 to 2000, an average of just over two per year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Historic flood events were the All Saints' Flood of 1304 and other floods in the years 1320, 1449, 1625, 1694, 1784 and 1825.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] From 1872, there exist regular and reliable records of water levels in the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The highest was the flood of 1872 when the water was an average of 2.43 m (8 ft 0 in) above sea level at Warnemünde and a maximum of 2.83 m (9 ft 3 in) above sea level in Warnemünde.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the last very heavy floods the average water levels reached 1.88 m (6 ft 2 in) above sea level in 1904, 1.89 m (6 ft 2 in) in 1913, 1.73 m (5 ft 8 in) in January 1954, 1.68 m (5 ft 6 in) on 2–4 November 1995 and 1.65 m (5 ft 5 in) on 21 February 2002.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] An arm of the North Atlantic Ocean, the Baltic Sea is enclosed by Sweden and Denmark to the west, Finland to the northeast, and the Baltic countries to the southeast.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It is about 1,600 km (990 mi) long, an average of 193 km (120 mi) wide, and an average of 55 metres (180 ft) deep.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The maximum depth is 459 m (1,506 ft) which is on the Swedish side of the centre.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The periphery amounts to about 8,000 km (5,000 mi) of coastline.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is one of the largest brackish inland seas by area, and occupies a basin (a *Zungenbecken*) formed by glacial erosion during the last few ice ages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The northern part of the Baltic Sea is known as the Gulf of Bothnia, of which the northernmost part is the Bay of Bothnia or Bothnian Bay.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The more rounded southern basin of the gulf is called Bothnian Sea and immediately to the south of it lies the Sea of Åland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Finland connects the Baltic Sea with Saint Petersburg.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Riga lies between the Latvian capital city of Riga and the Estonian island of Saaremaa.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Northern Baltic Sea lies between the Stockholm area, southwestern Finland, and Estonia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Western and Eastern Gotland basins form the major parts of the Central Baltic Sea or Baltic proper.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Bornholm Basin is the area east of Bornholm, and the shallower Arkona Basin extends from Bornholm to the Danish isles of Falster and Zealand.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the south, the Bay of Gdańsk lies east of the Hel Peninsula on the Polish coast and west of the Sambia Peninsula in Kaliningrad Oblast.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Bay of Pomerania lies north of the islands of Usedom/Uznam and Wolin, east of Rügen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Between Falster and the German coast lie the Bay of Mecklenburg and Bay of Lübeck.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The westernmost part of the Baltic Sea is the Bay of Kiel.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The three Danish Straits, the Great Belt, the Little Belt and The Sound (*Öresund*/*Øresund*), connect the Baltic Sea with the Kattegat and Skagerrak strait in the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The water temperature of the Baltic Sea varies significantly depending on exact location, season and depth.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] At the Bornholm Basin, which is located directly east of the island of the same name, the surface temperature typically falls to 0–5 °C (32–41 °F) during the peak of the winter and rises to 15–20 °C (59–68 °F) during the peak of the summer, with an annual average of around 9–10 °C (48–50 °F).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] A similar pattern can be seen in the Gotland Basin, which is located between the island of Gotland and Latvia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the deep of these basins the temperature variations are smaller.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] At the bottom of the Bornholm Basin, deeper than 80 m (260 ft), the temperature typically is 1–10 °C (34–50 °F), and at the bottom of the Gotland Basin, at depths greater than 225 m (738 ft), the temperature typically is 4–7 °C (39–45 °F).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Generally, offshore locations, lower latitudes and islands maintain maritime climates, but adjacent to the water continental climates are common, especially on the Gulf of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the northern tributaries the climates transition from moderate continental to subarctic on the northernmost coastlines.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] On the long-term average, the Baltic Sea is ice-covered at the annual maximum for about 45% of its surface area.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The ice-covered area during such a typical winter includes the Gulf of Bothnia, the Gulf of Finland, the Gulf of Riga, the archipelago west of Estonia, the Stockholm archipelago, and the Archipelago Sea southwest of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The remainder of the Baltic does not freeze during a normal winter, except sheltered bays and shallow lagoons such as the Curonian Lagoon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The ice reaches its maximum extent in February or March; typical ice thickness in the northernmost areas in the Bothnian Bay, the northern basin of the Gulf of Bothnia, is about 70 cm (28 in) for landfast sea ice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Freezing begins in the northern extremities of the Gulf of Bothnia typically in the middle of November, reaching the open waters of the Bothnian Bay in early January.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Bothnian Sea, the basin south of Kvarken, freezes on average in late February.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Finland and the Gulf of Riga freeze typically in late January.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In 2011, the Gulf of Finland was completely frozen on 15 February.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The ice extent depends on whether the winter is mild, moderate, or severe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In severe winters ice can form around southern Sweden and even in the Danish Straits.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] According to the 18th-century natural historian William Derham, during the severe winters of 1703 and 1708, the ice cover reached as far as the Danish Straits.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Frequently, parts of the Gulf of Bothnia and the Gulf of Finland are frozen, in addition to coastal fringes in more southerly locations such as the Gulf of Riga.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This description meant that the whole of the Baltic Sea was covered with ice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Since 1720, the Baltic Sea has frozen over entirely 20 times, most recently in early 1987, which was the most severe winter in Scandinavia since 1720.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] During the winter of 2010–11, which was quite severe compared to those of the last decades, the maximum ice cover was 315,000 km2 (122,000 sq mi), which was reached on 25 February 2011.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The ice then extended from the north down to the northern tip of Gotland, with small ice-free areas on either side, and the east coast of the Baltic Sea was covered by an ice sheet about 25 to 100 km (16 to 62 mi) wide all the way to Gdańsk.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This was brought about by a stagnant high-pressure area that lingered over central and northern Scandinavia from around 10 to 24 February.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] After this, strong southern winds pushed the ice further into the north, and much of the waters north of Gotland were again free of ice, which had then packed against the shores of southern Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The effects of the aforementioned high-pressure area did not reach the southern parts of the Baltic Sea, and thus the entire sea did not freeze over.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] However, floating ice was additionally observed near Świnoujście harbour in January 2010.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In recent years before 2011, the Bothnian Bay and the Bothnian Sea were frozen with solid ice near the Baltic coast and dense floating ice far from it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In 2008, almost no ice formed except for a short period in March.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] During winter, fast ice, which is attached to the shoreline, develops first, rendering ports unusable without the services of icebreakers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Level ice, ice sludge, pancake ice, and rafter ice form in the more open regions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The gleaming expanse of ice is similar to the Arctic, with wind-driven pack ice and ridges up to 15 m (49 ft).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Offshore of the landfast ice, the ice remains very dynamic all year, and it is relatively easily moved around by winds and therefore forms pack ice, made up of large piles and ridges pushed against the landfast ice and shores.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In spring, the Gulf of Finland and the Gulf of Bothnia normally thaw in late April, with some ice ridges persisting until May in the eastern extremities of the Gulf of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the northernmost reaches of the Bothnian Bay, ice usually stays until late May; by early June it is practically always gone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] However, in the famine year of 1867 remnants of ice were observed as late as 17 July near Uddskär.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Even as far south as Øresund, remnants of ice have been observed in May on several occasions; near Taarbaek on 15 May 1942 and near Copenhagen on 11 May 1771.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Drift ice was also observed on 11 May 1799.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The ice cover is the main habitat for two large mammals, the grey seal (*Halichoerus grypus*) and the Baltic ringed seal (*Pusa hispida botnica*), both of which feed underneath the ice and breed on its surface.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Of these two seals, only the Baltic ringed seal suffers when there is not adequate ice in the Baltic Sea, as it feeds its young only while on ice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The grey seal is adapted to reproducing also with no ice in the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The sea ice also harbours several species of algae that live in the bottom and inside unfrozen brine pockets in the ice.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Due to the often fluctuating winter temperatures between above and below freezing, the saltwater ice of the Baltic Sea can be treacherous and hazardous to walk on, in particular in comparison to the more stable fresh water-ice sheets in the interior lakes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea flows out through the Danish Straits; however, the flow is complex.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] A surface layer of brackish water discharges 940 km3 (230 cu mi) per year into the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Due to the difference in salinity, by salinity permeation principle, a sub-surface layer of more saline water moving in the opposite direction brings in 475 km3 (114 cu mi) per year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It mixes very slowly with the upper waters, resulting in a salinity gradient from top to bottom, with most of the saltwater remaining below 40 to 70 m (130 to 230 ft) deep.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The general circulation is anti-clockwise: northwards along its eastern boundary, and south along with the western one.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The difference between the outflow and the inflow comes entirely from fresh water.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] More than 250 streams drain a basin of about 1,600,000 km2 (620,000 sq mi), contributing a volume of 660 km3 (160 cu mi) per year to the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] They include the major rivers of north Europe, such as the Oder, the Vistula, the Neman, the Daugava and the Neva.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Additional fresh water comes from the difference of precipitation less evaporation, which is positive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] An important source of salty water is infrequent inflows (also known as major Baltic inflows or MBIs) of North Sea water into the Baltic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Such inflows, important to the Baltic ecosystem because of the oxygen they transport into the Baltic deeps, happen on average once per year, but large pulses that can replace the anoxic deep water in the Gotland Deep occur about once in ten years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Previously, it was believed that the frequency of MBIs had declined since 1980, but recent studies have challenged this view and no longer display a clear change in the frequency or intensity of saline inflows.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Instead, a decadal variability in the intensities of MBIs is observed with a main period of approximately 30 years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The water level is generally far more dependent on the regional wind situation than on tidal effects.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] However, tidal currents occur in narrow passages in the western parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Tides can reach 17 to 19 cm (6.7 to 7.5 in) in the Gulf of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The significant wave height is generally much lower than that of the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Quite violent, sudden storms sweep the surface ten or more times a year, due to large transient temperature differences and a long reach of the wind.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Seasonal winds also cause small changes in sea level, of the order of 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) .
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] According to the media, during a storm in January 2017, an extreme wave above 14 m (46 ft) has been measured and significant wave height of around 8 m (26 ft) has been measured by the FMI.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] A numerical study has shown the presence of events with 8 to 10 m (26 to 33 ft) significant wave heights.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Those extreme waves events can play an important role in the coastal zone on erosion and sea dynamics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is the world's largest brackish sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Only two other brackish waters are larger according to some measurements: The Black Sea is larger in both surface area and water volume, but most of it is located outside the continental shelf (only a small fraction is inland).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Caspian Sea is larger in water volume, but—despite its name—it is a lake rather than a sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The open surface waters of the Baltic Sea "proper" generally have a salinity of 0.3 to 0.9%, which is border-line freshwater.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The flow of freshwater into the sea from approximately two hundred rivers and the introduction of salt from the southwest builds up a gradient of salinity in the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The highest surface salinities, generally 0.7–0.9%, are in the southwestern most part of the Baltic, in the Arkona and Bornholm basins (the former located roughly between southeast Zealand and Bornholm, and the latter directly east of Bornholm).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] It gradually falls further east and north, reaching the lowest in the Bothnian Bay at around 0.3%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Drinking the surface water of the Baltic as a means of survival would actually hydrate the body instead of dehydrating, as is the case with ocean water.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] As saltwater is denser than freshwater, the bottom of the Baltic Sea is saltier than the surface.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] This creates a vertical stratification of the water column, a halocline, that represents a barrier to the exchange of oxygen and nutrients, and fosters completely separate maritime environments.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The difference between the bottom and surface salinities varies depending on location.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Overall it follows the same southwest to east and north pattern as the surface.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] At the bottom of the Arkona Basin (equalling depths greater than 40 m or 130 ft) and Bornholm Basin (depths greater than 80 m or 260 ft) it is typically 1.4–1.8%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Further east and north the salinity at the bottom is consistently lower, being the lowest in Bothnian Bay (depths greater than 120 m or 390 ft) where it is slightly below 0.4%, or only marginally higher than the surface in the same region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In contrast, the salinity of the Danish Straits, which connect the Baltic Sea and Kattegat, tends to be significantly higher, but with major variations from year to year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] For example, the surface and bottom salinity in the Great Belt is typically around 2.0% and 2.8% respectively, which is only somewhat below that of the Kattegat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The water surplus caused by the continuous inflow of rivers and streams to the Baltic Sea means that there generally is a flow of brackish water out through the Danish Straits to the Kattegat (and eventually the Atlantic).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Significant flows in the opposite direction, salt water from the Kattegat through the Danish Straits to the Baltic Sea, are less regular and are known as major Baltic inflows (MBIs).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The rating of mean discharges differs from the ranking of hydrological lengths (from the most distant source to the sea) and the rating of the nominal lengths.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Countries that border the sea: Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, Sweden.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Countries lands in the outer drainage basin: Belarus, Czech Republic, Norway, Slovakia, Ukraine.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea drainage basin is roughly four times the surface area of the sea itself.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] About 48% of the region is forested, with Sweden and Finland containing the majority of the forest, especially around the Gulfs of Bothnia and Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] About 20% of the land is used for agriculture and pasture, mainly in Poland and around the edge of the Baltic Proper, in Germany, Denmark, and Sweden.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] About 17% of the basin is unused open land with another 8% of wetlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Most of the latter are in the Gulfs of Bothnia and Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The rest of the land is heavily populated.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] About 85 million people live in the Baltic drainage basin, 15 million within 10 km (6 mi) of the coast and 29 million within 50 km (31 mi) of the coast.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Around 22 million live in population centres of over 250,000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] 90% of these are concentrated in the 10 km (6 mi) band around the coast.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Of the nations containing all or part of the basin, Poland includes 45% of the 85 million, Russia 12%, Sweden 10% and the others less than 6% each.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The relic of Scandinavian Glacier in white.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] is former seabed or archipelago: illustrated are sea levels immediately after the last ice age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea somewhat resembles a riverbed, with two tributaries, the Gulf of Finland and Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Geological surveys show that before the Pleistocene, instead of the Baltic Sea, there was a wide plain around a great river that palaeontologists call the Eridanos.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Several Pleistocene glacial episodes scooped out the river bed into the sea basin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] By the time of the last, or Eemian Stage (MIS 5e), the Eemian Sea was in place.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Sometimes the Baltic Sea is considered a very large estuary, with freshwater outflow from numerous rivers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] From that time the waters underwent a geologic history summarized under the names listed below.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Many of the stages are named after marine animals (e.g. the Littorina mollusc) that are clear markers of changing water temperatures and salinity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The land is still emerging isostatically from its depressed state, which was caused by the weight of ice during the last glaciation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The phenomenon is known as post-glacial rebound.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] Consequently, the surface area and the depth of the sea are diminishing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] The uplift is about eight millimetres per year on the Finnish coast of the northernmost Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p01] In the area, the former seabed is only gently sloping, leading to large areas of land being reclaimed in what are, geologically speaking, relatively short periods (decades and centuries).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The fauna of the Baltic Sea is a mixture of marine and freshwater species.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Among marine fishes are Atlantic cod, Atlantic herring, European hake, European plaice, European flounder, shorthorn sculpin and turbot, and examples of freshwater species include European perch, northern pike, whitefish and common roach.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Freshwater species may occur at outflows of rivers or streams in all coastal sections of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Otherwise, marine species dominate in most sections of the Baltic, at least as far north as Gävle, where less than one-tenth are freshwater species.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In the Bothnian Bay, roughly two-thirds of the species are freshwater.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In the far north of this bay, saltwater species are almost entirely absent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] For example, the common starfish and shore crab, two species that are very widespread along European coasts, are both unable to cope with the significantly lower salinity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Their range limit is west of Bornholm, meaning that they are absent from the vast majority of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Some marine species, like the Atlantic cod and European flounder, can survive at relatively low salinities but need higher salinities to breed, which therefore occurs in deeper parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The common blue mussel is the dominating animal species, and makes up more than 90% of the total animal biomass in the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] There is a decrease in species richness from the Danish belts to the Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The decreasing salinity along this path causes restrictions in both physiology and habitats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] However, even the most diverse sections of the Baltic Sea have far fewer species than the almost-full saltwater Kattegat, which is home to more than 1600 species from these groups.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The lack of tides has affected the marine species as compared with the Atlantic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Since the Baltic Sea is so young there are only two or three known endemic species: the brown alga *Fucus radicans* and the flounder *Platichthys solemdali*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Both appear to have evolved in the Baltic basin and were only recognized as species in 2005 and 2018 respectively, having formerly been confused with more widespread relatives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The tiny Copenhagen cockle (*Parvicardium hauniense*), a rare mussel, is sometimes considered endemic, but has now been recorded in the Mediterranean.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] However, some consider non-Baltic records to be misidentifications of juvenile lagoon cockles (*Cerastoderma glaucum*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Several widespread marine species have distinctive subpopulations in the Baltic Sea adapted to the low salinity, such as the Baltic Sea forms of the Atlantic herring and lumpsucker, which are smaller than the widespread forms in the North Atlantic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] A peculiar feature of the fauna is that it contains a number of glacial relict species, isolated populations of arctic species which have remained in the Baltic Sea since the last glaciation, such as the large isopod *Saduria entomon*, the Baltic subspecies of ringed seal, and the fourhorn sculpin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Some of these relicts are derived from glacial lakes, such as *Monoporeia affinis*, which is a main element in the benthic fauna of the low-salinity Bothnian Bay.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Cetaceans in the Baltic Sea are monitored by the countries bordering the sea and data compiled by various intergovernmental bodies, such as ASCOBANS.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In recent years, very small, but with increasing rates, fin whales and humpback whales migrate into Baltic sea including mother and calf pair.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Now extinct Atlantic grey whales (remains found from Gräsö along Bothnian Sea/southern Bothnian Gulf and Ystad) and eastern population of North Atlantic right whales that is facing functional extinction once migrated into Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Other notable megafauna include the basking sharks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Satellite images taken in July 2010 revealed a massive algal bloom covering 377,000 square kilometres (146,000 mi2) in the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The area of the bloom extended from Germany and Poland to Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Researchers of the phenomenon have found that algal blooms have occurred every summer for decades.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Fertilizer runoff from surrounding agricultural land has exacerbated the problem and led to increased eutrophication.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Approximately 100,000 km2 (38,610 sq mi) of the Baltic's seafloor (a quarter of its total area) is a variable dead zone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The more saline (and therefore denser) water remains on the bottom, isolating it from surface waters and the atmosphere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] This leads to decreased oxygen concentrations within the zone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] It is mainly bacteria that grow in it, digesting organic material and releasing hydrogen sulfide.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Because of this large anaerobic zone, the seafloor ecology differs from that of the neighbouring Atlantic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Plans to artificially oxygenate areas of the Baltic that have experienced eutrophication have been proposed by the University of Gothenburg and Inocean AB.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The proposal intends to use wind-driven pumps to pump oxygen-rich surface water to a depth of around 130 m.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] After World War II, Germany had to be disarmed, and large quantities of ammunition stockpiles were disposed directly into the Baltic Sea and the North Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Environmental experts and marine biologists warn that these ammunition dumps pose an environmental threat, with potentially life-threatening consequences to the health and safety of humans on the coastlines of these seas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Climate change, and pollution from agriculture and forestry, impose such strong effects on the ecosystems of the Baltic sea, that there is a concern the sea will turn from a carbon sink to a source of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] These include its current brackish water, the southern subbasin tendency to have a vertical stratification of the halocline, and the northern subbasin seasonal sea ice cover.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] There are many more projections but these have lower confidence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Construction of the Great Belt Bridge in Denmark (completed 1997) and the Øresund Bridge-Tunnel (completed 1999), linking Denmark with Sweden, provided a highway and railroad connection between Sweden and the Danish mainland (the Jutland Peninsula, precisely the Zealand).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The undersea tunnel of the Øresund Bridge-Tunnel provides for navigation of large ships into and out of the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The Baltic Sea is the main trade route for the export of Russian petroleum.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Countries neighbouring the Baltic Sea have expressed concerns about this since a major oil leak in a seagoing tanker would be especially disastrous for the Baltic given the slow exchange of water in the ecosystem.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The tourism industry surrounding the Baltic Sea is naturally concerned about oil pollution.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Much shipbuilding is carried out in the shipyards around the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The largest shipyards are at Gdańsk, Gdynia, and Szczecin, Poland; Kiel, Germany; Karlskrona and Malmö, Sweden; Rauma, Turku, and Helsinki, Finland; Riga, Ventspils, and Liepāja, Latvia; Klaipėda, Lithuania; and Saint Petersburg, Russia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Construction of the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link between Denmark and Germany is due to finish in 2029.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] It will be a three-bore tunnel carrying four motorway lanes and two rail tracks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Through the development of offshore wind power the Baltic Sea is expected to become a major source of energy for countries in the region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] According to the Marienborg Declaration, signed in 2022, all EU Baltic Sea states have announced their intentions to have 19.6 gigawatts of offshore wind in operation by 2030.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Critical maritime infrastructure (CMI) include pipelines, ports, undersea cables and energy installations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Following a series of incidents between 2022 and 2025, critical infrastructure in the Baltic Sea has drawn growing political attention.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In September 2022, both Nord Stream I and Nord Stream II were damaged by explosives close to Bornholm in Denmark.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In October 2023, the Balticconnector gas pipeline was damaged by the anchor of the Chinese container vessel *Newnew Polar Bear*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In November 2024, telecoms cables were damaged, another case of suspected sabotage from a Chinese bulk carrier, departing from a Russian port.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In December 2024, a ship registered in the Cook Islands which was thought to be part of a Russian shadow fleet, the *Estlink 2*, was suspected to have damaged internet cables.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] These incidents have led to responses from NATO, the European Union and national governments.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] NATO has increased its air and naval presence, as well as agreed to establish the Maritime Centre for the Security of Critical Undersea Infrastructure within NATO's Allied Maritime Command (MARCOM), among other cooperation efforts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The EU has updated its Maritime Security Strategy, launched an action plan and a coordination group for infrastructure protection, while national governments have strengthened surveillance, legal tools, and seabed defence capabilities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Aside from technical standards, political decisions influence what is deemed as "critical" infrastructure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Critical maritime infrastructure is deemed as critical since economies in today's society are dependent on this infrastructure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Therefore, they require an extra layer of protection, whether by security policies or military protection.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In the current geopolitical climate, CMI is facing challenges posed by hybrid warfare threats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Hybrid threats in the Baltic Sea are often associated with Russian actions and operate below the official threshold of war, which poses a political challenge.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The challenge posed by hybrid threats is that they operate in a grey area between peace and violence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] For example, the Nord Stream pipeline sabotage demonstrated this problem by exploitation of legal ambiguities, the complexity of attribution, and the disruption of alliance cohesion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The incident highlights the vulnerability of critical infrastructure and the absence of coherent political responses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Responding to hybrid threats requires sustained and coordinated efforts between civilian and military actors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] However, the maritime domain presents unique difficulties, including jurisdictional overlaps, fragmented responsibilities, and the challenge of adapting land-based security frameworks to the sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Hybrid tactics, such as uncrewed aerial vehicle (drone) surveillance, covert sabotage, and information manipulation, aim not only to damage infrastructure but also to undermine public trust and create strategic instability in the region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The Baltic Sea region in the post-Cold War era has for a long time been regarded as an area with little geopolitical tensions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] With the Soviet presence in the south, the American influence through the NATO members Denmark and Germany and the neutral states Sweden and Finland, an equilibrium existed, often referred to as the "Nordic balance".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] This balance also prolonged after the steady integration of the region into western institutions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] However, in recent years this geopolitical reality has increasingly been challenged by the neo-imperial ambitions of Russia, manifesting itself in aggression against Ukraine.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Russia has also pursued a strategy of regional dominance in the Baltic Sea, designating the regional sea as a zone of strategic influence in its naval doctrine published in 2022.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Yet, such a positioning in itself was significantly complicated by the accession of Sweden and Finland to NATO.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Against this geopolitical background, it becomes clear, why many of the recent infrastructure projects in the Baltic Sea were subject to big political debates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] These initiatives form part of broader efforts to enhance regional integration and bring the Baltic Sea states into closer alignment with the European Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In contrast, the Nord Stream pipelines, particularly Nord Stream 2, became a source of political controversy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Critics argued that the project would increase European dependence on Russian gas, bypass transit countries such as Ukraine and Poland, and undermine EU energy solidarity by strengthening Russia's leverage over countries like Germany.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Nord Stream 2 experienced prolonged delays and was ultimately suspended following the imposition of international sanctions against Russia after the invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In addition to political and economic controversies, the Nord Stream pipelines also became the subject of security-related concerns regarding their potential strategic implications in the Baltic Sea region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Prior to the 2022 sabotage of the Nord Stream pipelines, security experts and several Eastern European states had raised concerns that such infrastructure could be exploited by Russia for intelligence gathering and military purposes in the Baltic Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] These concerns gained renewed attention following the sabotage incident, which highlighted challenges in the legal and regulatory frameworks governing the protection of critical infrastructure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The difficulty in conclusively attributing the attack also drew attention to the limitations of existing mechanisms for responding to hybrid threats in the maritime domain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] For the first time ever, all the sources of pollution around an entire sea were made subject to a single convention, signed in 1974 by the then seven Baltic coastal states.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The 1974 Convention entered into force on 3 May 1980.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] In the light of political changes and developments in international environmental and maritime law, a new convention was signed in 1992 by all the states bordering on the Baltic Sea, and the European Community.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] After ratification, the Convention entered into force on 17 January 2000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The Convention covers the whole of the Baltic Sea area, including inland waters and the water of the sea itself, as well as the seabed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Measures are also taken in the whole catchment area of the Baltic Sea to reduce land-based pollution.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The convention on the Protection of the Marine Environment of the Baltic Sea Area, 1992, entered into force on 17 January 2000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The governing body of the convention is the Helsinki Commission, also known as HELCOM, or Baltic Marine Environment Protection Commission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The present contracting parties are Denmark, Estonia, the European Community, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, and Sweden.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The ratification instruments were deposited by the European Community, Germany, Latvia and Sweden in 1994, by Estonia and Finland in 1995, by Denmark in 1996, by Lithuania in 1997, and by Poland and Russia in November 1999.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The European Union (EU) is one core framework shaping regional security coordination in the Baltic Sea region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The EU has recognised this area as one of thirteen designated zones for territorial cooperation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Following the accession of the Baltic States in 2004, the Baltic Sea is now considered an EU internal sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) is the primary provider of a collective defence system.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] Following the accession of Finland in 2023 and Sweden in 2024, the majority of the states bordering the Baltic Sea have become members of NATO, simplifying the organisational geography of the region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The Nordic Defence Cooperation (NORDEFCO) is a military alliance comprising the Nordic countries of Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The objectives of this cooperation structure include improving the national defence of each country, identifying shared strategic interests, and promoting the development of coordinated, effective responses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The strategy paper 'Vision 2025' outlines plans to enhance collaboration with the Baltic states and transatlantic allies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The Council of the Baltic Sea States is an intergovernmental political organisation that focuses on regional cooperation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] It was established in 1992 and comprises ten European states and the European Union.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] The organisation serves as a forum for political dialogue in the region and follows three main objectives: Regional Identity, Safe & Secure Region, and Sustainable & Prosperous Region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baltic-sea-p02] It holds annual regional and international meetings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] A **bandwin** was a team of agricultural workers in the Scottish Lowlands before the agricultural revolution, who carried out the harvest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The bandwin was characteristically made up of two teams of two women and a man who acted as reapers and a bandster who gathered and bound the sheaves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The work of women in the bandwin was unusually almost as valued as that of the men.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The term was first recorded in 1642 in the Sheriffs records for Aberdeenshire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] It may be derived from the bands of stalks used to tie the sheaves of grain, or because it made up a band or group.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] Most members were women from the Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] Characteristically they were made up of seven members: six shearers using the crescent-shaped sickle, and a bandster who bound the sheaves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The reapers were divided into two teams, each of which worked two ridges of a runrig.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The bandster was usually a man and the two teams were ideally made up of two women and one man.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The man in each team cut the longest and strongest stalks in the run middle of the group.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The woman on the right hand side had the most laborious task, as she had to stretch to meet the adjacent ridge.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] The two women in a team would, as a result, change places every landing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] A bandster could bind the corn of two teams and the six reapers could cut two acres a day.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bandwin] In the mid-eighteenth century female reapers received 5d a day, male reapers 6d a day and the bandster 7d.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The term originates from the Latin term *barō*, via Old French.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The use of the title *baron* came to England via the Norman Conquest of 1066, then the Normans brought the title to Scotland and Southern Italy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] It later spread to Scandinavian and Slavic lands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The word *baron* comes from the Old French *baron*, from a Late Latin *barō* "man; servant, soldier, mercenary" (so used in Salic law; Alemannic law has *barus* in the same sense).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The scholar Isidore of Seville in the 7th century thought the word was from Greek βᾰρῠ́ς "heavy" (because of the "heavy work" done by mercenaries), but the word is presumably of Old Frankish origin, cognate with Old English *beorn* meaning "warrior, nobleman".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Cornutus in the first century already reports a word *barones* which he took to be of Gaulish origin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the Peerage of England, the Peerage of Great Britain, the Peerage of Ireland and the Peerage of the United Kingdom (but not in the Peerage of Scotland), barons form the lowest rank, placed immediately below viscounts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] A woman of baronial rank has the title **baroness**.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] After the Norman Conquest in 1066, the Norman dynasty introduced an adaptation of the French feudal system to the Kingdom of England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Initially, the term "baron" on its own was not a title or rank, but the "barons of the King" were the men of the king.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Previously, in the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of England, the king's companions held the title of earl and in Scotland, the title of thane.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] All who held their feudal barony "in-chief of the king", that is with the king as his immediate overlord, became alike *barones regis* ("barons of the king"), bound to perform a stipulated annual military service and obliged to attend his council.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Initially those who held land directly from the king by military service, from earls downwards, all bore alike the title of baron, which was thus the factor uniting all members of the ancient baronage as peers one of another.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Under King Henry II, the *Dialogus de Scaccario* already distinguished between greater barons, who held *per baroniam* by knight's service, and lesser barons, who held manors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Thus in this historical sense, lords of manors are barons, or freemen; however they are not entitled to be styled as such.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] John Selden writes in *Titles of Honour*, "The word *Baro* (Latin for 'baron') hath been also so much communicated, that not only all Lords of Mannors have been from ancient time, and are at this day called sometimes Barons (as in the stile of their Court Barons, which is *Curia Baronis, &c*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] These representatives developed into the knights of the shire, elected by the county court presided over by the sheriff, who themselves formed the precursor of the House of Commons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Thus appeared a definite distinction, which eventually had the effect of restricting to the greater barons alone the privileges and duties of peerage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Later, the king started to create new baronies in one of two ways: by a writ of summons directing a chosen man to attend Parliament, and in an even later development by letters patent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Writs of summons became the normal method in medieval times, displacing the method of feudal barony, but creation of baronies by letters patent is the sole method adopted in modern times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Since the adoption of summons by writ, baronies thus no longer relate directly to land-holding, and thus no more feudal baronies needed to be created from then on.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Following the *Modus Tenendi Parliamenta* of 1419, the Tenures Abolition Act 1660, the Feudal Tenure Act 1662, and the Fines and Recoveries Act 1834, titles of feudal barony became obsolete and without legal force.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The Tenures Abolition Act 1660 specifically states: baronies by tenure were converted into baronies by writ.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The rest ceased to exist as feudal baronies by tenure, becoming baronies in free socage, that is to say under a "free" (hereditable) contract requiring payment of monetary rents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the 20th century, Britain introduced the concept of non-hereditary life peers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] All appointees to this distinction have, except for the Duke of Edinburgh, been at the rank of baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In accordance with the tradition applied to hereditary peers, they too are formally addressed in parliament by their peers as "The Noble Lord".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In addition, baronies are often used by their holders as subsidiary titles, for example as courtesy titles for the son and heir of an Earl or higher-ranked peer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The Scottish baronial title tends to be used when a landed family is not in possession of any United Kingdom peerage title of higher rank, subsequently granted, or has been created a knight of the realm.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Several members of the royal family with the style of *Royal Highness* are also titled Barons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] For example, William, Prince of Wales is also The Baron of Renfrew and The Baron Carrickfergus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Some non-royal Barons are related to the royal family; for example, Maurice Roche, 6th Baron Fermoy is William's first cousin once removed, through William's late mother, Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the 4th Baron Fermoy's granddaughter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The title of baron (Irish: *barún*) was created in the Peerage of Ireland shortly after the Norman invasion of Ireland (1169).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Ireland's first baronies included Baron Athenry (1172), Baron Offaly (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] A person holding a peerage in the rank of baron is entitled to a coronet bearing six pearls around the rim, equally spaced and all of equal size and height.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The rim itself is neither jewelled nor "chased" (which is the case for the coronets of peers of higher degree).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The actual coronet is worn only for the coronation of a new monarch, but a baron can bear his coronet of rank on his coat of arms above the shield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In heraldry, the baron's coronet is shown with four of the balls visible.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Formally, barons are styled *The Right Honourable The Lord [Barony]* and barons’ wives are styled *The Right Honourable The Lady [Barony]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Baronesses in their own right, whether hereditary or for life, are either styled *The Right Honourable The Baroness [Barony]* or *The Right Honourable The Lady [Barony]*, mainly based on personal preference (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Lady Thatcher and Baroness Warsi, both life baronesses in their own right).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Less formally, one refers to or addresses a baron as *Lord [Barony]* and his wife as *Lady [Barony]*, and baronesses in their own right as *Baroness [X]* or *Lady [X]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In direct address, barons and baronesses can also be referred to as *My Lord*, *Your Lordship*, or *Your Ladyship or My Lady*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The husband of a baroness in her own right gains no title or style from his wife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Children of barons and baronesses in their own right, whether hereditary or for life, have the style *The Honourable [Forename] [Surname]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] After the death of the father or mother, the child may continue to use this style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Courtesy barons are styled *Lord [Barony]*, and their wives *Lady [Barony]*; the article "The" is always absent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] If the courtesy baron is not a Privy Counsellor, the style *The Right Honourable* will also be absent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] It is very common for the surnames of barons and baronesses to be identical to or included in the formal title of their barony.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] However, when addressed as a peer, the title of *Lord*, *Lady*, or *Baroness* is followed by the name of his or her barony, not his personal name.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This is relevant when a baron or baroness's title is completely different from his or her personal surname (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] William Thomson, Lord Kelvin) or includes a territorial designation in addition to his surname (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This also means that including a baron or baroness's forename before his or her title is incorrect and potentially misleading.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] For example, "Lady Margaret Thatcher" (as opposed to "Lady Thatcher") would imply that she was the daughter of an earl, marquess, or duke, or Lady of the Garter or Thistle not holding a peerage rather than a baroness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Likewise, in the case of men, "Lord Digby Jones" (as opposed to "Lord Jones of Birmingham") would imply that he was the younger son of a marquess or duke rather than a baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The United Kingdom has a policy of including titles of nobility on passports: the title is entered into the surname field and a standard observation is recorded giving the holder's full name and title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] A Baron would therefore record his surname as *Lord [Barony]*, and the observation would note that *The holder is The Right Honourable [given names] [surname] Lord [Barony]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] However, if the title of an applicant's peerage is different from his surname, he can choose whether to use his surname or title in the surname field.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] A baroness in her own right would substitute "Baroness" for "Lord", and the wife of a Baron would similarly substitute "Lady".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Titles of nobility are checked against Debrett's Peerage, Who's Who, or The London Gazette by the passport office on application.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Scotland, the rank of baron is a rank of the ancient nobility of the Baronage of Scotland and refers to the holder of a barony, formerly a feudal superiority or prescriptive barony attached to land erected into a free barony by Crown Charter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The Court of the Lord Lyon will officially recognise those possessing the dignity of baron on petition who meet certain criteria, and will grant them baronial arms with a helmet befitting their degree.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Scottish barons rank below Lords of Parliament and while noble have the status of minor baron, being a non-Peerage rank; as such it can be transferred by either inheritance or assignation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Sir Thomas Innes of Learney, in his *Scots Heraldry* (2nd Ed., p.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] 88, note 1), states that "The Act 1672, cap 47, specially qualifies the degrees thus: Nobles (i.e. peers, the term being here used in a restricted seventeenth-century English sense), Barons (i.e.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Lairds of baronial fiefs and their 'heirs', who, even if fiefless, are equivalent to heads of Continental baronial houses) and Gentlemen (apparently all other armigers)." Baronets and knights are evidently classed as 'Gentlemen' here and are of a lower degree than Barons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The Scottish equivalent of an English baron is a Lord of Parliament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Scottish barons were entitled to a red cap of maintenance (chapeau) turned up ermine if petitioning for a grant or matriculation of a coat of arms between the 1930s and 2004.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This chapeau is identical to the red cap worn by an English baron, but without the silver balls or gilt.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This is sometimes depicted in armorial paintings between the shield and the helmet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Additionally, if the baron is the head of a family, he may include a chiefly coronet which is similar to a ducal coronet, but with four strawberry leaves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Because the chapeau was a relatively recent innovation, a number of ancient arms of Scottish feudal barons do not display the chapeau.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Now, Scottish barons are principally recognised by the baron's helm, which in Scotland is a steel helmet with grille of three grilles, garnished in gold.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Occasionally, the great tilting-helm garnished with gold is shown, or a helmet befitting a higher rank, if held.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Scottish barons style their surnames similarly to Clan Chiefs if they own the caput, with the name of their barony following their name, as in *John Smith of Edinburgh, Baron of Edinburgh* otherwise *John Smith, Baron of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Most formally, and in writing, they are styled as *The Much Honoured Baron of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Their wives are styled *Lady Edinburgh*, or *The Baroness of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The phrase *Lady of Edinburgh* is wrong if the lady in question does not hold a Scottish barony in her own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Orally, Scottish barons may be addressed with the name of their barony, as in *Edinburgh* or else as *Baron* without anything else following, which if present would suggest a peerage barony.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Informally, when referring to a Scots baron in the third person, the name *Baron of [X]* is used or simply *[X]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] During the Ancien Régime, French baronies were very much like Scottish ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Feudal landholders who possessed a barony were entitled to style themselves as a baron (French: *baron*) if they were nobles; a *roturier* (commoner) could only be a *seigneur de la baronnie* (lord of the barony).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] French baronies could be sold freely until 1789, when the Constituent Assembly abolished feudal law.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The title of baron was assumed as a *titre de courtoisie* by many nobles, whether members of the Nobles of the Robe or cadets of Nobles of the Sword who held no title in their own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] 1804–1815) created a new imperial nobility in which *baron* appeared from 1808 as the second-lowest title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The titles were inherited through a male-only line of descent and could not be purchased.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In 1815, King Louis XVIII created a new peerage system and a Chamber of Peers, based on the British model.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Baron-peer was the lowest title, but the heirs to pre-1789 barons could remain barons, as could the elder sons of viscount-peers and the younger sons of count-peers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This peerage system was abolished in 1848.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The wife of a *Freiherr* (Baron) is called a *Freifrau* or sometimes *Baronin*, his daughter *Freiin* or sometimes *Baroness*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Families which had always held this status were called *Uradel* ('primordial/ancient/original nobility'), and were heraldically entitled to a three-pointed coronet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Families which had been ennobled at a definite point in time (*Briefadel* or "nobility by patent") had seven points on their coronet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] These families held their fief in vassalage from a suzerain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The holder of an allodial (i.e. suzerain-free) barony was thus called a Free Lord, or *Freiherr*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Subsequently, sovereigns in Germany conferred the title of *Freiherr* as a rank in the nobility, without implication of allodial or feudal status.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Since 1919, hereditary titles have had no legal status in Germany.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In modern, republican Germany, *Freiherr* and *Baron* remain heritable only as part of the legal surname (and may thereby be transmitted to husbands, wives and children, without implication of nobility).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Austria, hereditary titles have been completely banned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Thus, a member of the formerly reigning House of Habsburg or members of the former nobility would in most cases simply be addressed as *Herr/Frau (Habsburg)* in an official/public context, for instance in the media.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Still, in both countries, honorary styles like "His/Her (Imperial/Royal) Highness", "Serenity", etc. persist in social use as a form of courtesy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Generally, all legitimate males of a German baronial family inherit the title *Freiherr* or *Baron* from birth, as all legitimate daughters inherit the title of *Freiin* or *Baroness*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] As a result, German barons have been more numerous than those of such countries where primogeniture with respect to title inheritance prevails (or prevailed), such as France and the United Kingdom.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Italy, *barone* was the lowest rank of feudal nobility except for that of *signore* or *vassallo* (lord of the manor).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The title of baron was most generally introduced into southern Italy (including Sicily) by the Normans during the 11th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Whereas originally a barony might consist of two or more manors, by 1700 we see what were formerly single manors erected into baronies, counties or even marquisates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Since the early 1800s, when feudalism was abolished in the various Italian states, it has often been granted as a simple hereditary title without any territorial designation or *predicato*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The untitled younger son of a baron is a *nobile dei baroni* and in informal usage might be called a baron, while certain baronies devolve to heirs male general.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Since 1948 titles of nobility have not been recognised by the Italian state.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the absence of a nobiliary or heraldic authority in Italy there are, in fact, numerous persons who claim to be barons or counts without any basis for such claims.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Baron and noble (*nobile*) are hereditary titles and, as such, could only be created or recognised by the kings of Italy or (before 1860) the pre-unitary Italian states such as the Two Sicilies, Tuscany, Parma or Modena, or by the Holy See (Vatican) or the Republic of San Marino.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Beginning around 1800, a number of *signori* (lords of the manor) began to style themselves *barone* but in many cases this was not sanctioned legally by decree, while there was even less justification in the holder of any large (non-feudal) landed estate calling himself a baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Nevertheless, both were common practices.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In most of peninsular Italy the widespread medieval introduction of the title was Longobardic, while in Sicily and Sardinia it was coeval with Norman rule some centuries later, and one referred to the *baronage* when speaking of landed nobles generally.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The heraldic coronet of an Italian baron is a jewelled rim of gold surmounted by seven visible pearls, set upon the rim directly or upon stems; alternately, the French style coronet (entwined in a string of small pearls, with or without four bigger visible pearls set upon the rim) is used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the medieval era, some allodial and enfeoffed lands held by nobles were created or recognised as baronies by the Holy Roman Emperors, within whose realm most of the Low Countries lay.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Subsequently, the Habsburgs continued to confer the baronial title in the Southern Netherlands, first as kings of Spain and then, again, as emperors until abolition of the Holy Roman Empire, but these had become titular elevations rather than grants of new territory.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the Netherlands after 1815, titles of baron (Dutch: *baron* (m), *barones* (f)) authorised by previous monarchs (except those of the Napoleonic Kingdom of Holland) were usually recognised by the Dutch kings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] But such recognition was not automatic, having to be authenticated by the Supreme Council of Nobility and then approved by the sovereign.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This ceased to be possible after the Dutch constitution was revised in 1983.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] More than one hundred Dutch baronial families have been recognised.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The title is usually inherited by all males descended patrilineally from the original recipient of the title, although in a few noble families *baron* is the title of cadet family members, whilst in a few others it is heritable according to primogeniture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] After its secession in 1830, Belgium incorporated into its nobility all titles of baron borne by Belgian citizens, which had been recognised by the Netherlands since 1815.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In addition, its monarchs have since created or recognised other titles of baron, and the sovereign continues to exercise the prerogative to confer baronial and other titles of nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] *Baron* is the third lowest title within the nobility system above knight (French: *chevalier*, Dutch: *ridder*) and below *viscount*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] There are still a number of families in Belgium that bear the title of baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Luxembourg's monarch retains the right to confer the baronial title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Two of the grand duchy's prime ministers inherited baronial titles that were used during their tenures in office, Victor de Tornaco and Félix de Blochausen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Norway, king Magnus VI of Norway (1238–1280) replaced the title Lendmann with Baron, but in 1308 Haakon V abolished the title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The present corresponding title is *baron* in the Danish nobility and the Norwegian nobility, *friherre* in the Swedish nobility (*baron* is used orally, while it is written as *friherre*), and *vapaaherra* in the nobility of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the beginning, Finnish nobles were all without honorific titulature, and known simply as lords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Since the Middle Ages, each head of a noble family had been entitled to a vote in any of Finland's provincial diets whenever held, as in the realm's House of Nobility of the Riksdag of the Estates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In 1561, Sweden's King Eric XIV granted the hereditary titles of count and *vapaaherra* to some of these, but not all.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Although their cadet family members were not entitled to vote or sit in the Riksdag, they were legally entitled to the same title as the head of the family, but in customary address they became *Paroni* or *Paronitar*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Theoretically, in the 16th and 17th centuries, families elevated to *vapaaherra* status were granted a barony in fief, enjoying some rights of taxation and judicial authority.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Subsequently, the "barony" was titular, usually attached to a family property, which was sometimes entailed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Their exemptions from taxes on landed properties continued into the 20th century, although in the 19th century tax reforms narrowed this privilege.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Nobility creations continued until 1917, the end of Finland's grand ducal monarchy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Muscovite Russia had no traditional baronial titles of its own; they were introduced in early Imperial Russia by Peter the Great.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the hierarchy of nobility introduced by Peter the Great, barons (барон) ranked above untitled nobility and below counts (граф, *graf*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The styles "Your Well-born" (Ваше благородие, *Vashe blagorodiye*) and "Master Baron" (Господин барон, *Gospodin baron*) were used to address a Russian baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] There were two main groups of nobility which held the baronial title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] One was the Baltic German nobility, for which Russia merely recognised their pre-existing titles; the other was new barons created by the Emperors of Russia after 1721.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Like in many other countries, new baronial titles were often created by ennoblement of rich bourgeoisie.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The title of baron, along with the rest of the noble hierarchy, was abolished in December 1917 after the Bolshevik Revolution; however, certain leaders of the White movement like Baron Pyotr Wrangel and Roman von Ungern-Sternberg continued to use the title until the end of the Russian Civil War.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Spain, the title follows *Vizconde* in the noble hierarchy, and ranks above *Señor*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] *Baronesa* is the feminine form, for the wife of a baron or for a woman who has been granted the title in her own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In general, titles of *baron* created before the 19th century originate from the Crown of Aragon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] *Barons* lost territorial jurisdiction around the middle of the 19th century, and from then on the title became purely honorific.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Although most *barons* have not held the rank of *grandeza* as well, the title has been conferred in conjunction with the *grandeza*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] The sovereign continues to grant baronial titles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Like other major Western noble titles, *baron* is sometimes used to render certain titles in non-Western languages with their own traditions, even though they are necessarily historically unrelated and thus hard to compare, which are considered 'equivalent' in relative rank.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] This is the case with China's *nanjue* (*nan-chueh*) (Chinese: 男爵), hereditary title of nobility of the fifth rank, as well as its derivatives and adaptations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In some *republics* of continental Europe, the unofficial title of "Baron" retains a purely social prestige, with no particular political privileges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Armenian, the word "Baron" should not be confused with the similar word "Paron" (Armenian: Պարոն), which is a title given to ordinary men, equivalent to 'Sir' or 'Mr'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In Latvian, the term used by the Baltic German nobility is *barons* (female: *baronese*), although since the 19th century b*rīvkungs* (*brīvkundze*), a translation of Freiherr began to gain popularity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] In the Polynesian island monarchy of Tonga, as opposed to the situation in Europe, barons are granted this imported title (in English), alongside traditional chiefly styles, and continue to hold and exercise some political power.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] Barons and baronesses have appeared in various works of fiction.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/baron] For examples of fictional barons and baronesses, see List of fictional nobility#Barons and baronesses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Bere is a landrace adapted to growing on soils with a low pH (acidic) and to a short growing season with long hours of daylight, as found in the high latitudes of northern Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It is sown in the spring and harvested in the summer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Because of its very rapid growth rate, it is sown late but is often the first crop to be harvested.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It is known locally as *the 90-day barley*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Originally *bere* or *beir* or *bear* is a generic Scots word for barley of any kind, from Old English *bere*, "barley", and was used throughout the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Now it is used mainly in the north of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It often referred to barley of a lower yield, and the phrase "bear meal marriage" usually meant one that would not bring much wealth with it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Talking of the wide variety of crops in England, and crop rotation, Professor T.C.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Smout writes: "In Scotland, there is no evidence of such variation possibly because the range of crops was so much smaller — often only oats or bear (a primitive form of barley)".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Bere is a very old grain that may have been grown in Britain since Neolithic times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Another early term for it was "bygge" or "big", probably originating from *bygg*, the Old Norse term for barley.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It became well-adapted to the far north of Britain as successive generations of farmers grew it, selecting each year's seeds from the best plants of the previous year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, bere was an important crop in the Highlands and Islands region of Scotland, providing grain for milling and malting and straw for thatching and animal bedding.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It was also exported from Orkney and other ports in Scotland to Northern Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] The advent of higher-yielding barley varieties led to a deep decline in bere growing during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] It survives in cultivation today thanks to Barony Mills, a 19th-century watermill, which purchases the grain to produce *beremeal* which is used locally in bread, biscuits, and the traditional beremeal bannock.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] The Agronomy Institute at Orkney College UHI in Scotland has had a research programme on Bere since 2002.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] The programme is aimed at developing new markets for the crop and developing best practices for growing it more easily and with increased yield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] As a result of this research, several new markets (whisky, beer and biscuits) have been developed for Orkney Bere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] The crop is also being grown on the island of Islay, for whisky production by Bruichladdich Distillery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Bere flour has quite high levels of folate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Bere has a long history of use in making alcoholic beverages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] Historical accounts from the 15th century onward show that Orkney produced large amounts of malt and beer, most of it probably from bere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] An ancient tradition of making bere-based homebrew survives until this day in the islands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] During the 19th century, the Campbeltown distilleries used large quantities of bere in making Scotch whisky.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-early-modern-era/bere-grain] In the early 21st century some distillers began experimenting again with bere, and in 2006, the UK's most northern brewery released a bere-based microbrew.
